# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: voip-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711 passes audio signals in the frequency band of 300–3400 Hz and samples them at the rate of 8000 Hz, with the tolerance on that rate of 50 parts per million (ppm).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] It uses one of two different logarithmic companding algorithms: μ-law, which is used primarily in North America and Japan, and A-law, which is in use in most other countries outside North America.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Each companded sample is quantized as 8 bits, resulting in a 64 kbit/s bit rate.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711 is a required standard in many technologies, such as in the H.320 and H.323 standards.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] It can also be used for fax communication over IP networks (as defined in T.38 specification).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Two enhancements to G.711 have been published: **G.711.0** utilizes lossless data compression to reduce the bandwidth usage and **G.711.1** increases audio quality by increasing bandwidth.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711 defines two main companding algorithms, the μ-law algorithm and A-law algorithm.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Both are logarithmic, but A-law was specifically designed to be simpler for a computer to process.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] The standard also defines a sequence of repeating code values which defines the power level of 0 dB.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] The μ-law and A-law algorithms encode 14-bit and 13-bit signed linear PCM samples (respectively) to logarithmic 8-bit samples.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Thus, the G.711 encoder will create a 64 kbit/s bitstream for a signal sampled at 8 kHz.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711 μ-law tends to give more resolution to higher range signals while G.711 A-law provides more quantization levels at lower signal levels.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Where `s` is the sign bit, `s` is its inverse (i.e. positive values are encoded with MSB = *s* = 1), and bits marked `x` are discarded.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Note that the first column of the table uses different representation of negative values than the third column.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] So for example, input decimal value −21 is represented in binary after bit inversion as 1000000010100, which maps to 00001010 (according to the first row of the table).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] When decoding, this maps back to 1000000010101, which is interpreted as output value −21 in decimal.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] which is a 13-bit signed integer in the range ±1 to ±(212 − 26).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Note that no compressed code decodes to zero due to the addition of 0.5 (half of a quantization step).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] In addition, the standard specifies that all resulting even bits (LSB is even) are inverted before the octet is transmitted.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] This is to provide plenty of 0/1 transitions to facilitate the clock recovery process in the PCM receivers.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Thus, a silent A-law encoded PCM channel has the 8 bit samples coded 0xD5 instead of 0x80 in the octets.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] When data is sent over E0 (G.703), MSB (sign) is sent first and LSB is sent last.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] ITU-T STL defines the algorithm for decoding as follows (it puts the decoded values in the 13 most significant bits of the 16-bit output data type).
[src:voip-systems/g-711] See also "ITU-T Software Tool Library 2009 User's manual" that can be found at.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Final result is produced by decreasing the magnitude of this value by 33.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Where `s` is the sign bit, and bits marked `x` are discarded.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] In addition, the standard specifies that the encoded bits are inverted before the octet is transmitted.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Thus, a silent μ-law encoded PCM channel has the 8 bit samples transmitted 0xFF instead of 0x00 in the octets.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Adding 33 is necessary so that all values fall into a compression group and it is subtracted back when decoding.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] which is a 14-bit signed integer in the range ±0 to ±8031.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Note that 0 is transmitted as 0xFF, and −1 is transmitted as 0x7F, but when received the result is 0 in both cases.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711.0, also known as G.711 LLC, utilizes lossless data compression to reduce the bandwidth usage by as much as 50 percent.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] The *Lossless compression of G.711 pulse code modulation* standard was approved by ITU-T in September 2009.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711.1 *"Wideband embedded extension for G.711 pulse code modulation"* is a higher-fidelity extension to G.711, ratified in 2008 and further extended in 2012.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] G.711.1 allows a series of enhancement layers on top of a raw G.711 core stream (Layer 0): Layer 1 codes 16-bit audio in the same 4kHz narrowband, and Layer 2 allows 8kHz wideband using MDCT; each uses a fixed 16 kbps in addition to the 64 kbps core.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] They may be used together or singly, and each encodes the differences from the previous layer.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Ratified in 2012, Layer 3 extends Layer 2 to 16kHz "superwideband," allowing another 16 kbps for the highest frequencies, while retaining layer independence.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Peak bitrate becomes 96 kbps in original G.711.1, or 112 kbps with superwideband.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] No internal method of identifying or separating the layers is defined, leaving it to the implementation to packetize or signal them.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] A decoder that doesn't understand any set of fidelity layers may ignore or drop non-core packets without affecting it, enabling graceful degradation across any G.711 (or original G.711.1) telephony system with no changes.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Also ratified in 2012 was G.711.0 lossless extended to the new fidelity layers.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] Like G.711.0, full G.711 backward compatibility is sacrificed for efficiency, though a G.711.0 aware node may still ignore or drop layer packets it doesn't understand.
[src:voip-systems/g-711] The patents for G.711, released in 1972, have expired, so it may be used without the need for a license.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In electronics and telecommunications, **jitter** is the deviation from true periodicity of a presumably periodic signal, often in relation to a reference clock signal.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In clock recovery applications it is called **timing jitter**.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter is a significant, and usually undesired, factor in the design of almost all communications links.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter can be quantified in the same terms as all time-varying signals, e.g., root mean square (RMS), or peak-to-peak displacement.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Also, like other time-varying signals, jitter can be expressed in terms of spectral density.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter may be caused by electromagnetic interference and crosstalk with carriers of other signals.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter can cause a display monitor to flicker, affect the performance of processors in personal computers, introduce clicks or other undesired effects in audio signals, and cause loss of transmitted data between network devices.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The amount of tolerable jitter depends on the affected application.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] in the position of a clock's edge from where it would ideally be.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Maximum error committed by a clock under test in measuring a time interval for a given period of time.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The difference between any one clock period and the ideal or average clock period.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Hence, synchronous circuitry benefits from minimizing period jitter, so that the shortest clock period approaches the average clock period.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The difference in duration of any two adjacent clock periods.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In telecommunications, the unit used for the above types of jitter is usually the unit interval (UI) which quantifies the jitter in terms of a fraction of the transmission unit period.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] This unit is useful because it scales with clock frequency and thus allows relatively slow interconnects such as T1 to be compared to higher-speed internet backbone links such as OC-192.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Absolute units such as *picoseconds* are more common in microprocessor applications.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Units of *degrees* and *radians* are also used.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] If jitter has a Gaussian distribution, it is usually quantified using the standard deviation of this distribution.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] This translates to an RMS measurement for a zero-mean distribution.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Often, jitter distribution is significantly non-Gaussian.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] This can occur if the jitter is caused by external sources such as power supply noise.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In these cases, *peak-to-peak* measurements may be more useful.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Many efforts have been made to meaningfully quantify distributions that are neither Gaussian nor have a meaningful peak level.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] All have shortcomings but most tend to be good enough for the purposes of engineering work.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In computer networking, *jitter* can refer to packet delay variation, the variation (statistical dispersion) in the delay of the packets.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] One of the main differences between random and deterministic jitter is that deterministic jitter is bounded and random jitter is unbounded.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Random jitter, also called Gaussian jitter, is unpredictable electronic timing noise.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Random jitter typically follows a normal distribution due to being caused by thermal noise in an electrical circuit.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] in which the value of *n* is based on the BER required of the link.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A common BER used in communication standards such as Ethernet is 10−12.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In analog-to-digital and digital-to-analog conversion of signals, the sampling is normally assumed to be periodic with a fixed period—the time between every two samples is the same.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] If there is jitter present on the clock signal to the analog-to-digital converter or a digital-to-analog converter, the time between samples varies and instantaneous signal error arises.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The error is proportional to the slew rate of the desired signal and the absolute value of the clock error.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The effect of jitter on the signal depends on the nature of the jitter.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Random jitter tends to add broadband noise while deterministic jitter tends to add errant spectral components, *birdys*.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In some conditions, less than a nanosecond of jitter can reduce the effective bit resolution of a converter with a Nyquist frequency of 22 kHz to 14 bits.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Sampling jitter is an important consideration in high-frequency signal conversion, or where the clock signal is especially prone to interference.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In digital antenna arrays ADC and DAC jitters are the important factors determining the direction of arrival estimation accuracy and the depth of jammers suppression.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In the context of computer networks, packet jitter or packet delay variation (PDV) is the variation in latency as measured in the variability over time of the end-to-end delay across a network.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A network with constant delay has no packet jitter.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Packet jitter is expressed as an average of the deviation from the network mean delay.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] PDV is an important quality of service factor in assessment of network performance.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Transmitting a burst of traffic at a high rate followed by an interval or period of lower or zero rate transmission may also be seen as a form of jitter, as it represents a deviation from the average transmission rate.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] However, unlike the jitter caused by variation in latency, transmitting in bursts may be seen as a desirable feature, e.g. in variable bitrate transmissions.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Video or image jitter occurs when the horizontal lines of video image frames are randomly displaced due to the corruption of synchronization signals or electromagnetic interference during video transmission.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A model-based dejittering study has been carried out under the framework of digital image and video restoration.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter in serial bus architectures is measured by means of eye patterns.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] There are standards for jitter measurement in serial bus architectures.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The standards cover jitter tolerance, jitter transfer function and jitter generation, with the required values for these attributes varying among different applications.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Where applicable, compliant systems are required to conform to these standards.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Testing for jitter and its measurement is of growing importance to electronics engineers because of increased clock frequencies in digital electronic circuitry to achieve higher device performance.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Higher clock frequencies have commensurately smaller eye openings and thus impose tighter tolerances on jitter.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] For example, modern computer motherboards have serial bus architectures with eye openings of 160 picoseconds or less.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] This is extremely small compared to parallel bus architectures with equivalent performance, which may have eye openings on the order of 1000 picoseconds.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter is measured and evaluated in various ways depending on the type of circuit under test.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In all cases, the goal of jitter measurement is to verify that the jitter will not disrupt normal operation of the circuit.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Testing of device performance for jitter tolerance may involve injection of jitter into electronic components with specialized test equipment.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A less direct approach—in which analog waveforms are digitized and the resulting data stream analyzed—is employed when measuring pixel jitter in frame grabbers.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Anti-jitter circuits (AJCs) are a class of electronic circuits designed to reduce the level of jitter in a clock signal.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] AJCs operate by re-timing the output pulses so they align more closely to an idealized clock.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] They are widely used in clock and data recovery circuits in digital communications, as well as for data sampling systems such as the analog-to-digital converter and digital-to-analog converter.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Examples of anti-jitter circuits include phase-locked loop and delay-locked loop.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Jitter buffers or de-jitter buffers are buffers used to counter jitter introduced by queuing in packet-switched networks to ensure continuous playout of an audio or video media stream transmitted over the network.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The maximum jitter that can be countered by a de-jitter buffer is equal to the buffering delay introduced before starting the play-out of the media stream.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] In the context of packet-switched networks, the term *packet delay variation* is often preferred over *jitter*.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Some systems use sophisticated delay-optimal de-jitter buffers that are capable of adapting the buffering delay to changing network characteristics.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] The adaptation logic is based on the jitter estimates computed from the arrival characteristics of the media packets.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Adjustments associated with adaptive de-jittering involve introducing discontinuities in the media play-out, which may be noticeable to the listener or viewer.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] Adaptive de-jittering is usually carried out for audio play-outs that include voice activity detection, which allows the lengths of the silence periods to be adjusted, thus minimizing the perceptual impact of the adaptation.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer is a device that reduces jitter in a digital signal.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer usually consists of an elastic buffer in which the signal is temporarily stored and then retransmitted at a rate based on the average rate of the incoming signal.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A dejitterizer may not be effective in removing low-frequency jitter (wander).
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A filter can be designed to minimize the effect of sampling jitter.
[src:voip-systems/jitter] A jitter signal can be decomposed into intrinsic mode functions (IMFs), which can be further applied for filtering or dejittering.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The **Real-time Transport Protocol** (**RTP**) is a network protocol for delivering audio and video over IP networks.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in communication and entertainment systems that involve streaming media, such as telephony, video teleconference applications including WebRTC, television services and web-based push-to-talk features.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP typically runs over User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with the RTP Control Protocol (RTCP).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] While RTP carries the media streams (e.g., audio and video), RTCP is used to monitor transmission statistics and quality of service (QoS) and aids synchronization of multiple streams.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is one of the technical foundations of voice over IP and in this context is often used in conjunction with a signaling protocol such as the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), which establishes connections across the network.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio-Video Transport Working Group of the Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) and first published in 1996 as RFC 1889, which was then superseded by RFC 3550 in 2003.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Research on audio and video over packet-switched networks dates back to the early 1970s.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) published RFC 741 in 1977 and began developing RTP in 1992, and would go on to develop Session Announcement Protocol (SAP), the Session Description Protocol (SDP), and the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed for end-to-end, real-time transfer of streaming media.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The protocol provides facilities for jitter compensation and detection of packet loss and out-of-order delivery, which are common, especially during UDP transmissions on an IP network.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP allows data transfer to multiple destinations through IP multicast.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is regarded as the primary standard for audio/video transport in IP networks and is used with an associated profile and payload format.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The design of RTP is based on the architectural principle known as application-layer framing, where protocol functions are implemented in the application as opposed to the operating system's protocol stack.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Real-time multimedia streaming applications require timely delivery of information and often can tolerate some packet loss to achieve this goal.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, loss of a packet in an audio application may result in loss of a fraction of a second of audio data, which can be made unnoticeable with suitable error concealment algorithms.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The Transmission Control Protocol (TCP), although standardized for RTP use, is not normally used in RTP applications because TCP favors reliability over timeliness.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Instead, the majority of the RTP implementations are built on the User Datagram Protocol (UDP).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Other transport protocols specifically designed for multimedia sessions are SCTP and DCCP, although, as of 2012, they were not in widespread use.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP was developed by the Audio/Video Transport working group of the IETF standards organization.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used in conjunction with other protocols such as H.323 and RTSP.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification describes two protocols: RTP and RTCP.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used for the transfer of multimedia data, and the RTCP is used to periodically send control information and QoS parameters.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The data transfer protocol, RTP, carries real-time data.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Information provided by this protocol includes timestamps (for synchronization), sequence numbers (for packet loss and reordering detection) and the payload format, which indicates the encoded format of the data.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The control protocol, RTCP, is used for quality of service (QoS) feedback and synchronization between the media streams.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The bandwidth of RTCP traffic compared to RTP is small, typically around 5%.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP sessions are typically initiated between communicating peers using a signaling protocol, such as H.323, the Session Initiation Protocol (SIP), RTSP, or Jingle (XMPP).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] These protocols may use the Session Description Protocol to specify the parameters for the sessions.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP session is established for each multimedia stream.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Audio and video streams may use separate RTP sessions, enabling a receiver to selectively receive components of a particular stream.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP and RTCP design is independent of the transport protocol.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Applications most typically use UDP with port numbers in the unprivileged range (1024 to 65535).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) and the Datagram Congestion Control Protocol (DCCP) may be used when a reliable transport protocol is desired.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP specification recommends even port numbers for RTP and the use of the next odd port number for the associated RTCP session.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] A single port can be used for RTP and RTCP in applications that multiplex the protocols.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is used by real-time multimedia applications such as voice over IP, audio over IP, WebRTC, Internet Protocol television, and professional video over IP including SMPTE 2022 and SMPTE 2110.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP is designed to carry a multitude of multimedia formats, which permits the development of new formats without revising the RTP standard.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] To this end, the information required by a specific application of the protocol is not included in the generic RTP header.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] For each class of application (e.g., audio, video), RTP defines a *profile* and associated *payload formats*.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Every instantiation of RTP in a particular application requires a profile and payload format specifications.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The profile defines the codecs used to encode the payload data and their mapping to payload format codes in the protocol field *Payload Type* (PT) of the RTP header.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Each profile is accompanied by several payload format specifications, each of which describes the transport of particular encoded data.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The mapping of MPEG-4 audio/video streams to RTP packets is specified in RFC 3016, and H.263 video payloads are described in RFC 2429.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] RTP packets are created at the application layer and handed to the transport layer for delivery.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Each unit of RTP media data created by an application begins with the RTP packet header.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP header has a minimum size of 12 bytes.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] After the header, optional header extensions may be present.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] This is followed by the RTP payload, the format of which is determined by the particular class of application.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Used to indicate if there are extra padding bytes at the end of the RTP packet.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Padding may be used to fill up a block of certain size, for example, as required by an encryption algorithm.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The last byte of the padding contains the number of padding bytes that were added (including itself).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The extension header is application or profile specific.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Contains the number of CSRC identifiers (defined below) that follow the SSRC (also defined below).
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Signaling used at the application level in a profile-specific manner.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] If it is set, it means that the current data has some special relevance for the application.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Indicates the format of the payload and thus determines its interpretation by the application.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Values are profile specific and may be dynamically assigned.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Used by the receiver to play back the received samples at appropriate time and interval.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] When several media streams are present, the timestamps may be independent in each stream.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The granularity of the timing is application specific.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] For example, an audio application that samples data once every 125 μs (8 kHz, a common sample rate in digital telephony) would use that value as its clock resolution.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Video streams typically use a 90 kHz clock.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The clock granularity is one of the details that is specified in the RTP profile for an application.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] uniquely identifies the source of a stream.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The synchronization sources within the same RTP session will be unique.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] enumerate contributing sources to a stream that has been generated from multiple sources.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] indicates the length of the extension in 32-bit units, excluding the 32 bits of the extension header.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] A functional multimedia application requires other protocols and standards used in conjunction with RTP.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Protocols such as SIP, Jingle, RTSP, H.225 and H.245 are used for session initiation, control and termination.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] Other standards, such as H.264, MPEG and H.263, are used for encoding the payload data as specified by the applicable RTP profile.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] An RTP sender captures the multimedia data, then encodes, frames and transmits it as RTP packets with appropriate timestamps and increasing timestamps and sequence numbers.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The sender sets the *payload type* field in accordance with connection negotiation and the RTP profile in use.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] The RTP receiver detects missing packets and may reorder packets.
[src:voip-systems/real-time-transport-protocol] It decodes the media data in the packets according to the payload type and presents the stream to its user.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has evolved to integrate with mobile telephony, including Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over NR (Vo5G), enabling seamless voice communication over mobile data networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These advancements have extended VoIP's role beyond its traditional use in Internet-based applications.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] It has become a key component of modern mobile infrastructure, as 4G and 5G networks rely entirely on this technology for voice transmission.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The steps and principles involved in originating VoIP telephone calls are similar to traditional digital telephony and involve signaling, channel setup, digitization of the analog voice signals, and encoding.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead of being transmitted over a circuit-switched network, the digital information is packetized and transmission occurs as IP packets over a packet-switched network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] They transport media streams using special media delivery protocols that encode audio and video with audio codecs and video codecs.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Various codecs exist that optimize the media stream based on application requirements and network bandwidth; some implementations rely on narrowband and compressed speech, while others support high-fidelity stereo codecs.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The most widely used speech coding standards in VoIP are based on the linear predictive coding (LPC) and modified discrete cosine transform (MDCT) compression methods.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Popular codecs include the MDCT-based AAC-LD (used in FaceTime), the LPC/MDCT-based Opus (used in WhatsApp), the LPC-based SILK (used in Skype), μ-law, A-law versions of G.711, G.722, an open source voice codec known as iLBC, and a codec that uses only 8 kbit/s each way called G.729.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Early providers of voice-over-IP services used business models and offered technical solutions that mirrored the architecture of the legacy telephone network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Second-generation providers, such as Skype, built closed networks for private user bases, offering the benefit of free calls and convenience while potentially charging for access to other communication networks, such as the PSTN.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This limited the freedom of users to mix-and-match third-party hardware and software.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Third-generation providers, such as Google Talk, adopted the concept of federated VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These solutions typically allow dynamic interconnection between users in any two domains of the Internet, when a user wishes to place a call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In addition to VoIP phones, VoIP is also available on many personal computers and other Internet access devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Calls and SMS text messages may be sent via Wi-Fi or the carrier's mobile data network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP provides a framework for consolidation of all modern communications technologies using a single unified communications system.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has been adapted for use in mobile networks, leading to the development of advanced systems designed to support voice communication over modern data infrastructures.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Among these are Voice over LTE (VoLTE) and Voice over 5G (Vo5G), which enable voice communication over IP-based mobile infrastructures.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In contrast to traditional VoIP services, which often function independently of global telephone numbering systems, VoLTE and Vo5G are directly connected to mobile operators' infrastructures, providing seamless connectivity to the international telephone network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoLTE, introduced as part of 4G LTE networks, enables voice communication over an IP-based infrastructure initially developed for data transmission.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] It offers features such as high-definition voice (HD Voice) and faster call setup times compared to circuit-switched networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Vo5G, the 5G equivalent of VoLTE, utilizes the increased speed, reduced latency, and greater capacity of 5G networks to further enhance these capabilities.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Both VoLTE and Vo5G maintain compatibility with traditional public switched telephone networks (PSTNs), allowing users to make and receive calls to and from any telephone number worldwide.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These technologies differ from standalone VoIP services by being fully integrated with mobile network operators.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This integration ensures additional features such as emergency call support and quality-of-service guarantees, making them a central part of modern mobile telecommunication systems.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP has been implemented with proprietary protocols and protocols based on open standards in applications such as VoIP phones, mobile applications, and web-based communications.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A variety of functions are needed to implement VoIP communication.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some protocols perform multiple functions, while others perform only a few and must be used in concert.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Mass-market VoIP services use existing broadband Internet access, by which subscribers place and receive telephone calls in much the same manner as they would via the PSTN.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Full-service VoIP phone companies provide inbound and outbound service with direct inbound dialing.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Many offer unlimited domestic calling and sometimes international calls for a flat monthly subscription fee.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Phone calls between subscribers of the same provider are usually free when flat-fee service is not available.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP phone is necessary to connect to a VoIP service provider.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] It is increasingly common for telecommunications providers to use VoIP telephony over dedicated and public IP networks as a backhaul to connect switching centers and to interconnect with other telephony network providers; this is often referred to as *IP backhaul*.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Smartphones may have SIP clients built into the firmware or available as an application download.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Because of the bandwidth efficiency and low costs that VoIP technology can provide, businesses are migrating from traditional copper-wire telephone systems to VoIP systems to reduce their monthly phone costs.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2008, 80% of all new Private branch exchange (PBX) lines installed internationally were VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, in the United States, the Social Security Administration is converting its field offices of 63,000 workers from traditional phone installations to a VoIP infrastructure carried over its existing data network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP allows both voice and data communications to be run over a single network, which can significantly reduce infrastructure costs.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The prices of extensions on VoIP are lower than for PBX and key systems.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP switches may run on commodity hardware, such as personal computers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Rather than closed architectures, these devices rely on standard interfaces.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP devices have simple, intuitive user interfaces, so users can often make simple system configuration changes.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Dual-mode phones enable users to continue their conversations as they move between an outside cellular service and an internal Wi-Fi network, so that it is no longer necessary to carry both a desktop phone and a cell phone.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Maintenance becomes simpler as there are fewer devices to oversee.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP solutions aimed at businesses have evolved into unified communications services that treat all communications—phone calls, faxes, voice mail, e-mail, web conferences, and more—as discrete units that can all be delivered via any means and to any handset, including cellphones.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Two kinds of service providers are operating in this space: one set is focused on VoIP for medium to large enterprises, while another is targeting the small-to-medium business (SMB) market.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Skype, which originally marketed itself as a service among friends, began to cater to businesses in 2009, providing free-of-charge connections between any users on the Skype network and connecting to and from ordinary PSTN telephones for a charge.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In general, the provision of VoIP telephony systems to organizational or individual users can be divided into two primary delivery methods: private or on-premises solutions, or externally hosted solutions delivered by third-party providers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] On-premises delivery methods are more akin to the classic PBX deployment model for connecting an office to local PSTN networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] While many use cases still remain for private or on-premises VoIP systems, the wider market has been gradually shifting toward *Cloud* or *Hosted* VoIP solutions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Hosted systems are also generally better suited to smaller or personal use VoIP deployments, where a private system may not be viable for these scenarios.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, this will be one or more data centers with geographic relevance to the end-user(s) of the system.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This infrastructure is external to the user of the system and is deployed and maintained by the service provider.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Endpoints, such as VoIP telephones or softphone applications (apps running on a computer or mobile device), will connect to the VoIP service remotely.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These connections typically take place over public internet links, such as local fixed WAN breakout or mobile carrier service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In the case of a private VoIP system, the primary telephony system itself is located within the private infrastructure of the end-user organization.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Usually, the system will be deployed on-premises at a site within the direct control of the organization.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This can provide numerous benefits in terms of QoS control (see below), cost scalability, and ensuring privacy and security of communications traffic.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] However, the responsibility for ensuring that the VoIP system remains performant and resilient is predominantly vested in the end-user organization.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This is not the case with a Hosted VoIP solution.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Private VoIP systems can be physical hardware PBX appliances, converged with other infrastructure, or they can be deployed as software applications.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Generally, the latter two options will be in the form of a separate virtualized appliance.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] However, in some scenarios, these systems are deployed on bare metal infrastructure or IoT devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] With some solutions, such as 3CX, companies can attempt to blend the benefits of hosted and private on-premises systems by implementing their own private solution but within an external environment.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples can include data center collocation services, public cloud, or private cloud locations.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For on-premises systems, local endpoints within the same location typically connect directly over the LAN.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For remote and external endpoints, available connectivity options mirror those of Hosted or Cloud VoIP solutions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] However, VoIP traffic to and from the on-premises systems can often also be sent over secure private links.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Examples include personal VPN, site-to-site VPN, private networks such as MPLS and SD-WAN, or via private SBCs (Session Border Controllers).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] While exceptions and private peering options do exist, it is generally uncommon for those private connectivity methods to be provided by Hosted or Cloud VoIP providers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Communication on the IP network is perceived as less reliable in contrast to the circuit-switched public telephone network because it does not provide a network-based mechanism to ensure that data packets are not lost, and are delivered in sequential order.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] It is a best-effort network without fundamental quality of service (QoS) guarantees.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice, and all other data, travels in packets over IP networks with fixed maximum capacity.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP implementations may face problems with latency, packet loss, and jitter.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] By default, network routers handle traffic on a first-come, first-served basis.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Fixed delays cannot be controlled as they are caused by the physical distance the packets travel.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] They are especially problematic when satellite circuits are involved because of the long distance to a geostationary satellite and back; delays of 400–600 ms are typical.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Latency can be minimized by marking voice packets as being delay-sensitive with QoS methods such as DiffServ.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Network routers on high-volume traffic links may introduce latency that exceeds permissible thresholds for VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Excessive load on a link can cause congestion and associated queueing delays and packet loss.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This signals a transport protocol like TCP to reduce its transmission rate to alleviate the congestion.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] But VoIP usually uses UDP, not TCP, because recovering from congestion through retransmission usually entails too much latency.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] So QoS mechanisms can avoid the undesirable loss of VoIP packets by immediately transmitting them ahead of any queued bulk traffic on the same link, even when the link is congested by bulk traffic.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP endpoints usually have to wait for the completion of transmission of previous packets before new data may be sent.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Although it is possible to preempt (abort) a less important packet in mid-transmission, this is not commonly done, especially on high-speed links where transmission times are short even for maximum-sized packets.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] An alternative to preemption on slower links, such as dialup and digital subscriber line (DSL), is to reduce the maximum transmission time by reducing the maximum transmission unit.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] But since every packet must contain protocol headers, this increases relative header overhead on every link traversed.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The receiver must resequence IP packets that arrive out of order and recover gracefully when packets arrive too late or not at all.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Packet delay variation results from changes in queuing delay along a given network path due to competition from other users for the same transmission links.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP receivers accommodate this variation by storing incoming packets briefly in a playout buffer, deliberately increasing latency to improve the chance that each packet will be on hand when it is time for the voice engine to play it.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The added delay is thus a compromise between excessive latency and excessive dropout, i.e., momentary audio interruptions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Although jitter is a random variable, it is the sum of several other random variables that are at least somewhat independent: the individual queuing delays of the routers along the Internet path in question.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Motivated by the central limit theorem, jitter can be modeled as a Gaussian random variable.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This suggests continually estimating the mean delay and its standard deviation and setting the playout delay so that only packets delayed more than several standard deviations above the mean will arrive too late to be useful.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In practice, the variance in latency of many Internet paths is dominated by a small number (often one) of relatively slow and congested bottleneck links.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Most Internet backbone links are now so fast (e.g., 10 Gbit/s) that their delays are dominated by the transmission medium (e.g., optical fiber) and the routers driving them do not have enough buffering for queuing delays to be significant.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A number of protocols have been defined to support the reporting of quality of service (QoS) and quality of experience (QoE) for VoIP calls.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These include RTP Control Protocol (RTCP) extended reports, SIP RTCP summary reports, H.460.9 Annex B (for H.323), H.248.30 and MGCP extensions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are exchanged between IP endpoints on an occasional basis during a call, and an end-of-call message is sent via SIP RTCP summary report or one of the other signaling protocol extensions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP metrics reports are intended to support real-time feedback related to QoS problems, the exchange of information between the endpoints for improved call quality calculation and a variety of other applications.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] DSL modems typically provide Ethernet connections to local equipment, but inside they may actually be Asynchronous Transfer Mode (ATM) modems.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] They use ATM Adaptation Layer 5 (AAL5) to segment each Ethernet packet into a series of 53-byte ATM cells for transmission, reassembling them back into Ethernet frames at the receiving end.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Using a separate virtual circuit identifier (VCI) for voice over IP has the potential to reduce latency on shared connections.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM's potential for latency reduction is greatest on slow links because worst-case latency decreases with increasing link speed.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A full-size (1500 byte) Ethernet frame takes 94 ms to transmit at 128 kbit/s but only 8 ms at 1.5 Mbit/s.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] If this is the bottleneck link, this latency is probably small enough to ensure good VoIP performance without MTU reductions or multiple ATM VCs.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The latest generations of DSL, VDSL and VDSL2, carry Ethernet without intermediate ATM/AAL5 layers, and they generally support IEEE 802.1p priority tagging so that VoIP can be queued ahead of less time-critical traffic.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] ATM has substantial header overhead: 5/53 = 9.4%, roughly twice the total header overhead of a 1500-byte Ethernet frame.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This *ATM tax* is incurred by every DSL user, whether or not they take advantage of multiple virtual circuits – and few can.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Several protocols are used in the data link layer and physical layer for quality-of-service mechanisms that help VoIP applications work well even in the presence of network congestion.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The quality of voice transmission is characterized by several metrics that may be monitored by network elements and by the user agent hardware or software.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Such metrics include network packet loss, packet jitter, packet latency (delay), post-dial delay, and echo.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The metrics are determined by VoIP performance testing and monitoring.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A VoIP media gateway controller (aka Class 5 Softswitch) works in cooperation with a media gateway (aka IP Business Gateway) and connects the digital media stream, so as to complete the path for voice and data.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Gateways include interfaces for connecting to standard PSTN networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Ethernet interfaces are also included in modern systems, which are specially designed to link calls that are passed via VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] E.164 is a global numbering standard for both the PSTN and public land mobile network (PLMN).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Most VoIP implementations support E.164 to allow calls to be routed to and from VoIP subscribers and the PSTN/PLMN.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP implementations can also allow other identification techniques to be used.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, Skype allows subscribers to choose *Skype names* (usernames) whereas SIP implementations can use Uniform Resource Identifier (URIs) similar to email addresses.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Often VoIP implementations employ methods of translating non-E.164 identifiers to E.164 numbers and vice versa, such as the Skype-In service provided by Skype and the E.164 number to URI mapping (ENUM) service in IMS and SIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Echo can also be an issue for PSTN integration.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Common causes of echo include impedance mismatches in analog circuitry and an acoustic path from the receive to transmit signal at the receiving end.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Local number portability (LNP) and mobile number portability (MNP) also impact VoIP business.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Number portability is a service that allows a subscriber to select a new telephone carrier without requiring a new number to be issued.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Typically, it is the responsibility of the former carrier to "map" the old number to the undisclosed number assigned by the new carrier.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This is achieved by maintaining a database of numbers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A dialed number is initially received by the original carrier and quickly rerouted to the new carrier.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Multiple porting references must be maintained even if the subscriber returns to the original carrier.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The Federal Communications Commission (FCC) mandates carrier compliance with these consumer-protection stipulations.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In November 2007, the FCC in the United States released an order extending number portability obligations to interconnected VoIP providers and carriers that support VoIP providers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A voice call originating in the VoIP environment also faces least-cost routing (LCR) challenges to reach its destination if the number is routed to a mobile phone number on a traditional mobile carrier.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] LCR is based on checking the destination of each telephone call as it is made, and then sending the call via the network that will cost the customer the least.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This rating is subject to some debate, given the complexity of call routing created by number portability.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] With MNP in place, LCR providers can no longer rely on using the network root prefix to determine how to route a call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Instead, they must now determine the actual network of every number before routing the call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Therefore, VoIP solutions also need to handle MNP when routing a voice call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In countries without a central database, like the UK, it may be necessary to query the mobile network about which home network a mobile phone number belongs to.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP increases in the enterprise markets because of LCR options, VoIP needs to provide a certain level of reliability when handling calls.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A telephone connected to a land line has a direct relationship between a telephone number and a physical location, which is maintained by the telephone company and available to emergency responders via the national emergency response service centers in the form of emergency subscriber lists.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] When an emergency call is received by a center, the location is automatically determined from its databases and displayed on the operator console.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In IP telephony, no such direct link between location and communications end point exists.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Even a provider having wired infrastructure, such as a DSL provider, may know only the approximate location of the device, based on the IP address allocated to the network router and the known service address.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some ISPs do not track the automatic assignment of IP addresses to customer equipment.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] IP communication provides for device mobility.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For example, a residential broadband connection may be used as a link to a virtual private network of a corporate entity, in which case the IP address being used for customer communications may belong to the enterprise, not the residential ISP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Such off-premises extensions may appear as part of an upstream IP PBX.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] On mobile devices, e.g., a 3G handset or USB wireless broadband adapter, the IP address has no relationship with any physical location known to the telephony service provider, since a mobile user could be anywhere in a region with network coverage, even roaming via another cellular company.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] At the VoIP level, a phone or gateway may identify itself by its account credentials with a Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) registrar.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In such cases, the Internet telephony service provider (ITSP) knows only that a particular user's equipment is active.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Service providers often provide emergency response services by agreement with the user who registers a physical location and agrees that, if an emergency number is called from the IP device, emergency services are provided to that address only.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Such emergency services are provided by VoIP vendors in the United States by a system called Enhanced 911 (E911), based on the Wireless Communications and Public Safety Act.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The VoIP E911 emergency-calling system associates a physical address with the calling party's telephone number.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] All VoIP providers that provide access to the public switched telephone network are required to implement E911, a service for which the subscriber may be charged.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] "VoIP providers may not allow customers to opt out of 911 service." The VoIP E911 system is based on a static table lookup.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike in cellular phones, where the location of an E911 call can be traced using assisted GPS or other methods, the VoIP E911 information is accurate only if subscribers keep their emergency address information current.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Sending faxes over VoIP networks is sometimes referred to as Fax over IP (FoIP).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Transmission of fax documents was problematic in early VoIP implementations, as most voice digitization and compression codecs are optimized for the representation of the human voice and the proper timing of the modem signals cannot be guaranteed in a packet-based, connectionless network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A standards-based solution for reliably delivering fax-over-IP is the T.38 protocol.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The T.38 protocol is designed to compensate for the differences between traditional packet-less communications over analog lines and packet-based transmissions, which are the basis for IP communications.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The fax machine may be a standard device connected to an analog telephone adapter (ATA), or it may be a software application or dedicated network device operating via an Ethernet interface.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Originally, T.38 was designed to use UDP or TCP transmission methods across an IP network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some newer high-end fax machines have built-in T.38 capabilities, which are connected directly to a network switch or router.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In T.38 each packet contains a portion of the data stream sent in the previous packet.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Two successive packets have to be lost to actually lose data integrity.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Telephones for traditional residential analog service are usually connected directly to telephone company phone lines, which provide direct current to power most basic analog handsets independently of locally available electrical power.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP phones and VoIP telephone adapters connect to routers or cable modems, which typically depend on the availability of mains electricity or locally generated power.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers use customer premises equipment (e.g., cable modems) with battery-backed power supplies to assure uninterrupted service for up to several hours in case of local power failures.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Such battery-backed devices are typically designed for use with analog handsets.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP service providers implement services to route calls to other telephone services of the subscriber, such as a cellular phone, in the event that the customer's network device is inaccessible to terminate the call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure calls are possible using standardized protocols such as Secure Real-time Transport Protocol.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Most of the facilities for creating a secure telephone connection over traditional phone lines, such as digitizing and digital transmission, are already in place with VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] It is necessary only to encrypt and authenticate the existing data stream.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Automated software, such as a virtual PBX, may eliminate the need for personnel to greet and switch incoming calls.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The security concerns for VoIP telephone systems are similar to those of other Internet-connected devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This means that hackers with knowledge of VoIP vulnerabilities can perform denial-of-service attacks, harvest customer data, record conversations, and compromise voicemail messages.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Compromised VoIP user account or session credentials may enable an attacker to incur substantial charges from third-party services, such as long-distance or international calling.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The technical details of many VoIP protocols create challenges in routing VoIP traffic through firewalls and network address translators, used to interconnect to transit networks or the Internet.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Private session border controllers are often employed to enable VoIP calls to and from protected networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Other methods to traverse NAT devices involve assistive protocols such as STUN and Interactive Connectivity Establishment (ICE).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Standards for securing VoIP are available in the Secure Real-time Transport Protocol (SRTP) and the ZRTP protocol for analog telephony adapters, as well as for some softphones.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] IPsec is available to secure point-to-point VoIP at the transport level by using opportunistic encryption.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Though many consumer VoIP solutions do not support encryption of the signaling path or the media, securing a VoIP phone is conceptually easier to implement using VoIP than on traditional telephone circuits.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A result of the lack of widespread support for encryption is that it is relatively easy to eavesdrop on VoIP calls when access to the data network is possible.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Free open-source solutions, such as Wireshark, facilitate capturing VoIP conversations.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Government and military organizations use various security measures to protect VoIP traffic, such as voice over secure IP (VoSIP), secure voice over IP (SVoIP), and secure voice over secure IP (SVoSIP).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The distinction lies in whether encryption is applied in the telephone endpoint or in the network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over secure IP may be implemented by encrypting the media with protocols such as SRTP and ZRTP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Secure voice over IP uses Type 1 encryption on a classified network, such as SIPRNet.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Public Secure VoIP is also available with free GNU software and in many popular commercial VoIP programs via libraries, such as ZRTP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In June 2021, the National Security Agency (NSA) released comprehensive documents describing the four attack planes of a communications system – the network, perimeter, session controllers and endpoints – and explaining security risks and mitigation techniques for each of them.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice over IP protocols and equipment provide caller ID support that is compatible with the PSTN.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Many VoIP service providers also allow callers to configure custom caller ID information.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Wireline telephones which are manufactured in, imported to, or intended to be used in the US with Voice over IP service, on or after February 28, 2020, are required to meet the hearing aid compatibility requirements set forth by the Federal Communications Commission.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP has drastically reduced the cost of communication by sharing network infrastructure between data and voice.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A single broadband connection has the ability to transmit multiple telephone calls.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] As the popularity of VoIP grows, governments are becoming more interested in regulating VoIP in a manner similar to PSTN services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Throughout the developing world, particularly in countries where regulation is weak or captured by the dominant operator, restrictions on the use of VoIP are often imposed, including in Panama where VoIP is taxed, Guyana, where VoIP is prohibited.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In Ethiopia, where the government is nationalizing telecommunication service, it is a criminal offense to offer services using VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The country has installed firewalls to prevent international calls from being made using VoIP.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] These measures were taken after the popularity of VoIP reduced the income generated by the state-owned telecommunications company.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In Canada, the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission regulates telephone service, including VoIP telephony service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP services operating in Canada are required to provide 9-1-1 emergency service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] A general distinction is usually made between VoIP services that function over managed networks (via broadband connections) and VoIP services that function over unmanaged networks (essentially, the Internet).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The relevant EU Directive is not clearly drafted concerning obligations that can exist independently of market power (e.g., the obligation to offer access to emergency calls), and it is impossible to say definitively whether VoIP service providers of either type are bound by them.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In Oman, it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services, to the extent that websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Violations may be punished with fines of 50,000 Omani Rial (about 130,317 US dollars), a two-year prison sentence or both.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In 2009, police raided 121 Internet cafes throughout the country and arrested 212 people for using or providing VoIP services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In September 2017, Saudi Arabia lifted the ban on VoIPs, in an attempt to reduce operational costs and spur digital entrepreneurship.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United Arab Emirates (UAE), it is illegal to provide or use unauthorized VoIP services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Websites of unlicensed VoIP providers have been blocked.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Some VoIP services, such as Skype, were allowed.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In January 2018, internet service providers in UAE blocked all VoIP apps, including Skype, but permitting only 2 government-approved VoIP apps (C'ME and BOTIM).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In opposition, a petition on *Change.org* garnered over 5000 signatures, in response to which the website was blocked in UAE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] On March 24, 2020, the United Arab Emirates loosened restrictions on VoIP services earlier prohibited in the country, to ease communication during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] However, popular instant messaging applications such as WhatsApp, Skype, and FaceTime remained blocked from being used for voice and video calls, constricting residents to use paid services from the country's state-owned telecom providers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In India, it is legal to use VoIP, but it is illegal to have VoIP gateways inside India.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] This effectively means that people who have PCs can use them to make a VoIP call to other computers but not to a normal phone number.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign-based VoIP server services are illegal to use in India.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Internet telephony is permitted to the ISP with restrictions.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] PC / a device / Adapter conforming to the standard of any international agencies like ITU or IETF, etc., in India to PSTN/PLMN abroad.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Any device / Adapter conforming to standards of International agencies like ITU, IETF etc., connected to ISP node with static IP address to similar device / Adapter; within or outside India.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Except whatever is described in condition (ii) above, no other form of Internet Telephony is permitted.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In India no Separate Numbering Scheme is provided to the Internet Telephony.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Presently the 10-digit Numbering allocation based on E.164 is permitted to the Fixed Telephony, GSM, CDMA wireless service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] For Internet Telephony, the numbering scheme shall only conform to IP addressing Scheme of Internet Assigned Numbers Authority (IANA).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Translation of E.164 number / private number to IP address allotted to any device and vice versa, by ISP to show compliance with IANA numbering scheme is not permitted.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The Internet Service Licensee is not permitted to have PSTN/PLMN connectivity.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Voice communication to and from a telephone connected to PSTN/PLMN and following E.164 numbering is prohibited in India.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In South Korea, only providers registered with the government are authorized to offer VoIP services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Unlike many VoIP providers, most of whom offer flat rates, Korean VoIP services are generally metered and charged at rates similar to terrestrial calling.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Foreign VoIP providers encounter high barriers to government registration.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] In the United States, the FCC requires all interconnected VoIP service providers to comply with requirements comparable to those for traditional telecommunications service providers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP operators also receive the benefit of certain US telecommunications regulations, including an entitlement to interconnection and exchange of traffic with incumbent local exchange carriers via wholesale carriers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Providers of *nomadic* VoIP service—those who are unable to determine the location of their users—are exempt from state telecommunications regulation.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] Another legal issue that the US Congress is debating concerns changes to the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The issue in question is calls between Americans and foreigners.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] The NSA is not authorized to tap Americans' conversations without a warrant—but the Internet, and specifically VoIP does not draw as clear a line to the location of a caller or a call's recipient as the traditional phone system does.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] As VoIP's low cost and flexibility convince more and more organizations to adopt the technology, surveillance for law enforcement agencies becomes more difficult.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p01] VoIP technology has also increased federal security concerns because VoIP and similar technologies have made it more difficult for the government to determine where a target is physically located when communications are being intercepted, and that creates a whole set of new legal challenges.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] Danny Cohen first demonstrated a form of packet voice in 1973 which was developed into Network Voice Protocol which operated across the early ARPANET.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] On the early ARPANET, real-time voice communication was not possible with uncompressed pulse-code modulation (PCM) digital speech packets, which had a bit rate of 64 kbps, much greater than the 2.4 kbps bandwidth of early modems.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] The solution to this problem was linear predictive coding (LPC), a speech coding data compression algorithm that was first proposed by Fumitada Itakura of Nagoya University and Shuzo Saito of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone (NTT) in 1966.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC was capable of speech compression down to 2.4 kbps, leading to the first successful real-time conversation over ARPANET in 1974, between Culler-Harrison Incorporated in Goleta, California, and MIT Lincoln Laboratory in Lexington, Massachusetts.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC has since been the most widely used speech coding method.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] Code-excited linear prediction (CELP), a type of LPC algorithm, was developed by Manfred R.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] LPC algorithms remain an audio coding standard in modern VoIP technology.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] In the two decades following the 1974 demo, various forms of packet telephony were developed and industry interest groups formed to support the new technologies.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] Soon after it became an established area of interest in commercial labs of the major IT concerns, notably at AT&T, where Marian Croak and her team filed many patents related to the technology.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] By the late 1990s, the first softswitches became available, and new protocols, such as H.323, MGCP and Session Initiation Protocol (SIP) gained widespread attention.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] In the early 2000s, the proliferation of high-bandwidth always-on Internet connections to residential dwellings and businesses spawned an industry of Internet telephony service providers (ITSPs).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-ip-p02] The development of open-source telephony software, such as Asterisk PBX, fueled widespread interest and entrepreneurship in voice-over-IP services, applying new Internet technology paradigms, such as cloud services to telephony.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] To make a VoLTE call, the device, its firmware, and the mobile telephone providers on each end, as well as the inter-carrier connectivity must all implement the service in the area, and be able to work together.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE has been marketed as "HD voice" by some carriers, but this is a broader concept.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Moreover, HD+ (EVS) is used only in LTE and NR; HD voice was available in 3G too.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE is based on the IP Multimedia Subsystem (IMS) architectural framework, with specific profiles for control and media planes of voice service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This facilitates VoLTE on the LTE wireless broadband service defined by GSMA in PRD IR.92.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] The approach results in the voice service (control and media planes) being delivered as data flows within the LTE data bearer, with no dependency on (or ultimately, requirement for) the circuit-switched voice network to be in the call path.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] By August 2019, these numbers had risen to 262 operators investing in VoLTE in 120 countries and 194 operators with launched VoLTE-HD voice services in 91 countries.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE Roaming historically was required to make VoLTE Calls when roaming on another 4G/LTE network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Now countries with only 3G cores use 3G-to-VoLTE Roaming Interworking.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Devices without VoLTE Roaming cannot make VoLTE calls when roaming on another network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE Roaming uses the S8HR Architecture, this architecture routes the calls to the home mobile network or to a 3G home network using 3G-to-VoLTE Roaming Interworking .
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Roaming devices that lack VoLTE Roaming support can use 2G or 3G Networks (if available) for making and receiving calls (via Circuit Switched Fallback).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In countries without either 2G or 3G Networks, Roaming devices will not have access to call service from the connected Roaming Network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE Roaming Support requires an Android Device with Android 12 (2021) or newer or an iPhone with iOS 15 (2021) or newer.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] As of April 2023 Devices from Android 4 - 11 made up approximately 70% of the Global Android Device Market according to Google.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] These older devices are largely in demographics that are less likely to roam.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Not all devices that have been sold as 'VoLTE capable' support making calls to Emergency Numbers over 4G/LTE with VoLTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Some carriers and manufacturers have disabled the ability for phones to call Emergency Services with VoLTE and the devices are reliant on 2G or 3G Networks to make calls to Emergency Services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In 2022 at the European Emergency Number Association (EENA) Conference Telecoms Expert Rudolf van der Berg made a presentation to the Conference outlining serious compatibility issues with VoLTE Calling and Emergency Calling.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] One of the major issues he raised is that many 4G/LTE Phones (both European & International) are completely unable to call (911/112) Emergency services without the presence of 2G/3G (Circuit Switched Calling) Networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] A device can have working VoLTE Calling (IMS Registration) on a network but may not be able to successfully make calls to emergency numbers over 4G.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] For Android devices there are methods to test a device for 4G Emergency Calling support, however such testing can require third-party software and tools to perform.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Simply dialing an Emergency Number on a 4G device is **not** sufficient to test if a device can make VoLTE Emergency Calls.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Depending on signal strength and other factors a device may default to 2G or 3G networks (if available).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Furthermore, a 4G/LTE device may say *“Emergency Calls Only”* within the system settings or notifications area but that message does not prove the device can actually make an Emergency call over 4G/LTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Additionally a device may be configured for 4G Emergency Calls in a given region but fail to connect when placing a 4G Call in another country.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] These devices will generally get stuck on 'calling' and the call will never go through, even though a 2G or 3G network is available.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In March 2024 prior to the Switch-off of 3G Networks in Australia, the Federal Government announced that more than 740,000 4G VoLTE enabled phones may no longer be able to call Emergency Services after the 3G Networks were switched off.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In early April 2024 this number was increased to more than 1 million devices in the media with no change to the government reporting.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] After the completion of the review the number was less than 70,000 of devices that may not be able to call Emergency Services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Telstra was originally set to switch off their 3G Network on 30 June 2024.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Telstra extended their switch off to 31 August in early May 2024.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] On 14 August 2024, Telstra and Optus further extended the 3G switch off date to 28 October 2024.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Vodafone completed their 3G switch off in early January 2024.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE has been supported by all Qualcomm Snapdragon chipsets since at least 2014 (e.g.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Snapdragon 800/801), but some Android device manufacturers disabled it in software.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Manufacturers of many devices omitted the carrier network configurations/profiles required to support VoLTE calling on all networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Unlike calling with 2G and 3G, there is no single configuration for VoLTE that all devices and networks support.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Some networks support the GSMA IR.92 'Open Market Device' Configuration.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This configuration is intended to be a generic/global VoLTE configuration that can be used by Open Market (non-carrier) devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] 4G or LTE devices that lack native VoLTE calling support are reliant on a 2G or 3G network to make or receive calls via circuit-switched fallback (CSFB), and will otherwise have no call service.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] A device marketed as having VoLTE support may only be able to make calls on certain networks, due to varying network configurations and VoLTE standardisation issues.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In some instances (depending on brand, market, or region), devices have been sold that are unable to make VoLTE calls on any network, while the same devices purchased directly from a carrier (with carrier software) support VoLTE on that carrier's network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Some handsets purchased from another carrier or from another market may have software that is not configured to support VoLTE on all networks within a given country.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This issue primarily affects Android and other non-Apple devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] The iPhone 6 (2014) and newer, with at least iOS 10, support VoLTE calling on most networks.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] The iPhone 5 and 5s do not support VoLTE calling, even though they include LTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] For example, for an Android device to have VoLTE calling on the Telstra network, the device needs to be running a Telstra modem configuration.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Devices that are running the GSMA 'Open Market Device' configuration or a configuration from another carrier cannot make VoLTE calls on the Telstra network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This prevents Telstra customers from using Open Market Devices.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Open Market configuration devices can work on competing Australian providers Optus & Vodafone.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] With some Qualcomm based Android devices it is possible to modify the device firmware with special software and manually load a compatible carrier modem configuration, enabling VoLTE calling; a carrier may not recognise the device as supported, though it works correctly.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] For example, starting in May 2024 Telstra starting forcing a pre-recorded message with all outbound calls advising affected customers of the need to upgrade in advance of the 3G shutdown in August.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] However even customers with modified devices with working VoLTE calling on Telstra were hearing the message every time they made a 4G VoLTE call.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This is due to Telstra relying on established lists of 'compatible' devices (i.e.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Android users are able to confirm if VoLTE is working by checking for the Device 'IMS Status' within a hidden Radio Info Debug menu.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] If the IMS Status shows "**IMS Registration: Registered**" and "**Voice over LTE: Available**" then VoLTE is enabled and working.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] An IMS Status of "**Not Registered**" and "**Voice over LTE: Unavailable**" indicates VoLTE is not enabled or working.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] However the IMS Status debug **does not** confirm working 4G Emergency Calling support.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] For VoLTE calling to be "Available" on a device, VoLTE has to be both provisioned/enabled in the Firmware and a carrier compatible modem configuration/profile must be loaded on the device.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Typically the modem configurations are automatically loaded by the device firmware when inserting a sim card.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] However not all devices are configured to detect the sim cards for all networks and enable VoLTE Calling.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] The IMS Status debug can also indicate if Wi-Fi Calling (Voice over Wi-Fi) and Video Calling (ViLTE/Video Telephony) are available.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] (Note: For Wi-Fi Calling to say Available the device has to be connected to a suitable Wi-Fi Network).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Additionally, devices with a "UT Interface" status of "Unavailable" will be unable to change Call Forwarding or Call Busy Settings over 4G/LTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Note: UT Interface is not required for VoLTE Calling, UT Interface is only required to change supplementary service settings (i.e. call forwarding) on a 4G/LTE only network.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Devices without an "Available" UT Interface are reliant on 2G/3G networks to change call forwarding/busy settings.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Beginning in August 2012, MetroPCS launched the world's first commercial VoLTE services in Dallas, Texas, in the United States, alongside the first VoLTE phone, the LG Connect 4G.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In May 2014, Singtel introduced the world's first commercial "full-featured" VoLTE service in Singapore, only in combination with Galaxy Note 3, it was subsequently expanded.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In June 2014, KT showcased the world's first cross-border roaming services based on Voice over LTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] The South Korean operator partnered with China Mobile to develop VoLTE roaming services.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In November 2014, Verizon and AT&T announced the companies are enabling VoLTE-to-VoLTE connections between their respective customers.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] VoLTE interoperability between Verizon and AT&T customers began in 2015.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Testing and design were performed between both companies using third party networks such as Alcatel-Lucent.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This was stated to have been completed in November 2017.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] On July 11, 2015, SEATEL Cambodia announced the world's first commercial 100% VoLTE service without 2G/3G in Cambodia.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] As of 2020, almost all new phones for sale have the potential to support VoLTE.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] On December 31, 2022, Verizon shut down their CDMA network, therefore requiring devices to support LTE or 5G.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Customers with CDMA-only devices and LTE devices without VoLTE support would have been required to switch to a VoLTE-capable device by that date.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] As of March 2021, less than 1% of Verizon's customers were still using 3G, and many of the 3G-connected devices are integrated devices, such as smart utility meters and home burglar alarms.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Additionally, certain Verizon-compatible handsets were blocked from Verizon's CDMA network even before December 31, 2022, even if the device supported CDMA (for instance, unlocked devices with support for Sprint or China Telecom), therefore requiring VoLTE support when used on Verizon.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This includes 5G-capable and OnePlus handsets.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Devices lacking CDMA support starting with the Pixel 6 and iPhone 14 series as well as select older devices sold on GSM carriers will only work on Verizon in VoLTE mode.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] To ensure compatibility, 3GPP demand at least AMR-NB codec (narrow band), but the recommended speech codec for VoLTE is Adaptive Multi-Rate Wideband (AMR-WB), also known under the trademark HD Voice after GSMA's certification program.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This codec is mandated in 3GPP networks that are capable of 16 kHz sampling.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] In addition, many carriers and devices can use Enhanced Voice Services (EVS).
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This is an up to superwideband (20–16,000 Hz) or fullband (20–20,000 Hz) codec backwards-compatible with AMR-WB.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] This codec is also known under the trademark HD Voice+, after GSMA's certification program.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] GSMA has proposed to make EVS mandatory just like AMR-WB.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] (Both the carrier(s), any interconnect and the two calling devices must be capable of using the codec for it to be used.) The AMR-WB+ codec has a wide bit-rate range, from 5.2 to 48 kbit/s.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] EVS offers a wide range of bit rates from 5.9 kbit/s to 128 kbit/s, allowing service providers to *optimize network capacity and call quality as desired* for their service, so VoLTE does not ensure high call quality.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] Fraunhofer IIS has previously demonstrated an implementation of the AAC-ELD codec in VoLTE that they call "Full-HD Voice".
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] It has not gained any standard status or real-world adoption.
[src:voip-systems/voice-over-lte] They have since reused the term "Full-HD Voice" for EVS in fullband mode (HD+ is also used).
